<p>
The form is being submitted to a PHP script using the POST method.
It consists of a set of check boxes that will be passed to PHP as an array
called "topping".
</p><p>
We create an image button to be used to submit the form. It is given a name of
'pizzas' and the image src is "pizza-chef.jpg" located in the same directory or folder
as the HTML form. When the user clicks on this picture, the form will be submitted.
</p><p>
On line 9 of the PHP script, if the user has posted the form, there will be a
value in the $_POST array, the expression will test true, and the block will be entered.
</p><p>
The x/y coordinates represent the place on the image (pixel position) where the
user clicked his or her mouse button.
</p><p>
To check whether or not the form was submitted, you can test if these variables
are not empty with the empty() function: <code>if (!empty($coord1)</code>
</p></li>
<li><p>
Self-Processing HTML Forms
</p><p>
Rather than creating a separate HTML document to display a form and another PHP
script to process the user input, you might want to combine the HTML document
containing the form and the PHP script that processess it all into one script.
</p><p>
This is done by assigning the <b>$_SERVER['PHP_SELF']</b> array to the action
attribute of the HTML &lt;form&gt; tag.
</p><p>
When the user submits the form information by pressing the submit button,
the action attribute of the form references the URL of the same page that
displayed the form.
</p><p>
Because both the HTML form data and the PHP processing code are in the same
script, you will need a conditional check in your PHP program to see if the
form has been submitted.
</p><p>
For example, you can check to see if a field has a value, the submit button
has been clicked, or check the request method used. The following examples
demonstrate how this is done.
</p></li>
<li><p>
Checking If the Form Was Submitted
</p><p>
This example shows script that checks whether a form was submitted.
</p>
<h4>
Filename: self.php 
</h4>
<blockquote><small>
<div class="disp2">
