</small></blockquote>
<p>
The PHP isset() function checks to see if the form has been submitted using the
POST method. If it has, the program continues at line 4; if not, then program
control goes to line 11, and the form will be displayed in the browser.
</p><p>
The superglobal <b>$_SERVER['PHP_SELF']</b> contains information about the path
where this script is found starting at the document root of the server,
not the root of the file system.
</p></li>
<li><p>
Using Hidden Fields
</p><p>
If your Web page contains multiple forms, you can use hidden fields to help
identify what form needs to be processed by giving each form its own name.
</p><p>
By checking the existence and value of the hidden field, you can determine which
form should be displayed and when it should be processed.
</p><p>
You can also use hidden fields to include information that can be used when
processing the form but is something that you do not care to display, such as
the date the form was created, your name, and so on.
</p>
<h4>
Filename: hidden.php 
